<font color="#FF0000">STEADY HAND</font><br>
<tt>Sat Jul 26 12:54:29 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I respect your comments.  Your gentle strength pervades your thoughts.  I apologize to you for allowing my PTSD to get out of hand.  I am guilty of all white or all black, all good or all bad... all or nothing.  I over react to rejection.  Winston Churchill said something to the effect, &quot;the noble eagle does not pay heed to noisey sparrows.&quot;  Perhaps I should heed those words.<br>
I spent a lot of time hauling men into battle, evacuating them under fire, resupplying them with water and ammunition, and after the battle turned, I would haul out the dead and those with serious but non life threatening wounds.  I would take a quick look at the KIA&quot;s to see if any of them where living passengers that I had transported into the LZ.  I realize now that I should not have done that.  Because, I would often find one or two.<br>
At sundown, someplace remote from the battle sites, I would help my crewchief and doorgunner wash blood urine and feces off the cargo deck.  My emotions would become ping pong balls.  I wanted to be out there with them, but at the same time... I was glad that I was not.  I was not preoccupied with political thoughts I simply wanted my brothers to live.  After the washing, repairing combat damage, servicing, refueling and rearming was done it would be late and I would go and look for something to eat.  Always I would pray that they would make it through the night, at least until I could get back out there and help them at dawn.  My guilt would abate enough so that I could fall asleep while the mosquitoes buzzed and cannons fired H &amp; I missions somewhere near the perimeter wire.<br>
I can't help it.  I still want to reach out and help those who were there.  I don't want them in prison, sleeping under the bridge, commiting suicide or even being hungry.  Most of all I don't want them abused now by armchair quarterbacks.  I don't care about how or why we were crapped on.  I just want to wash it off and stop people from fouling us again.<br>
The tenacity of spirit, displayed by Cook Barela gives me hope that others will hold up their heads.<br>
The level headed approach that you and Arthur display remind me that I need to temper my own spirit.  I don't know why I react so strongly.<br>
It don't matter, anyway.
<p><code>-- eramon@edumaster.net  (Edward Ramon) </code><p>


